sols_latex:
Using the formula given in the hint, we know that the median \emph{m}
must satisfy the integral:

\begin{align*}
\frac12 = \int_0^m \frac3{\pi} \frac1{1+t^2}\,dt
\end{align*}

Thus, we evaluate the integral above and then solve for \emph{m}.

\begin{align*}
\frac12 &= \int_0^m \frac3{\pi} \frac1{1+t^2}\,dt  \\
&=  \frac3{\pi}\arctan(m) 
\end{align*}

hence $m = \tan(\pi/6) = 1/\sqrt{3}$.

(Or $m = \tan(\frac{\arctan \sqrt{3}}2)$.)

statement_latex:
A professor never finishes his class on time. The time of delay is given
by the probability density function

\begin{align*}
p(t) = \frac{k}{1+t^2}, \text{ where } 0 < t < \sqrt{3}
\end{align*}

You can use the facts that $\displaystyle \arctan(0) = 0$ and
$\arctan(\sqrt{3}) = \pi/3$.

\textbf{(c)} What is the median delay?

